Lessons to Highlight¶



1- "automatic" graphical inspections save you time
2- missingno highlights potential data gaps automatically
3- AND you still need to inspect your data manually

Our Approach to the Project¶


0 - locate all people and project/office locations
... analyze + map + map pairwise combinations

1- validate locations - postcode API
2- errors - throw out rows with errors & tell client about sources to fix
3- get geo data
4- find distances & times between locations - Google API create map

Limitations to consider - speed of postcode API, cost of google distance matrix

strategy - --(min cost/time) ==> get API and analysis working ==> then productize
-- take data in small bites
-- save intermediate results & iterate

In [12]:
def check_postcodes_exist(postcodes_unique):
    """
    Function to confirm if UK postcodes exist or not
    
    :param postcodes_unique: list of unique postcodes in a list
    :return two lists, separating correct from incorrect postcodes
    """
    
    postcodes_unique = set(postcodes_unique)
    postcodes_unique_exist = []
    postcodes_unique_nonexist =[]

    for postcode_to_test in postcodes_unique:
        client = PostCodeClient()
        # library returns a string that "looks like" a dict
        # so we parse result by json loads
        test_result = json.loads(client.validatePostCode(postcode_to_test))
        postcode_tested = postcode_to_test

        if test_result.get("result") != True:
            postcodes_unique_nonexist.append(postcode_tested)
        else:
            postcodes_unique_exist.append(postcode_tested)
    
    return postcodes_unique_exist, postcodes_unique_nonexist

def get_geo_data(source_dataframe):
    """
    Function to get geodata from the UK PostCodeClient API
    
    :param source_dataframe: input_dataframe, must contain column titled 'postcode'
    :return dataframe with rows of postcodes with geo data; one result per row
    """
    
    client = PostCodeClient()

    postcodes_unique = source_dataframe['postcode'].unique().tolist()
    
    # feed only postcodes that exist to geolocate API
    [postcodes_unique_exist, postcodes_unique_nonexist] = \
    check_postcodes_exist(postcodes_unique)

    # define headers we want in final dataframe; setup dataframe
    # 28 data elements available
    # e.g. exclude:  northings, Westminster Parliamentary Constituency, etc.
    header_columns = ['postcode', 'latitude','longitude','region', 'country']
    results_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(columns=header_columns)
    
    for lookup_code in postcodes_unique_exist:
        result_raw = client.getLookupPostCode(lookup_code)
        result_json = json.loads(result_raw)
        result_flattened = json_normalize(result_json['result'])

        # get only the columns we want
        resulting_row = result_flattened[header_columns]
        # append result to our dataframe
        results_dataframe = results_dataframe.append(resulting_row)

    return results_dataframe

# GOAL - create function to merge geo data with source DataFrame

def merge_geo_data(source_dataframe):
    """
    Function merges  geo data with source DataFrame
    
    :param source_dataframe: DataFrame with UK postcodes
    :return new dataframe with appended geo data: 'postcode', 'latitude','longitude','region', 'country' for each code
    
    """
    # get new geo data using existing function
    dataframe_results = get_geo_data(source_dataframe) 
    
    # merge with a LEFT join, since the left table is our master CSV - we don't want to introduce any NaN values
    source_dataframe = pd.merge(left=source_dataframe, 
                                right=dataframe_results, how='left')
    
    return source_dataframe

Google Distance Matrix API¶

Google Distance Matrix - Overview¶

https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/distance-matrix/intro

https://pypi.org/project/google-distance-matrix/

10 main parameters you can include:

  • origin & destination / format
  • when travelling - seconds since epoch (00:00:00 Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), Thursday, 1 January 1970)
  • units (metric/imperial)
  • travel modes: driving, walking, transit, etc.
  • transit mode: bus, subway, train, tram or rail
  • arrival time (or departure)

In [20]:
# Hidden - seconds since epoch; needed by Google API
# timestamp - create reusable function, that can be applied as a lambda or inserted as a variable
import datetime


def seconds_since_epoch_utc(target_datetime):
    """
    Function computes seconds since the epoch for a date/time object
    
    :param target_datetime: the target date and time in UTC
    :return INT of unix time in seconds since the epoch; needed as input for google distance matrix
    
    useful notes:
    target_datetime = datetime.datetime(target_datetime)  # e.g. 2018, 8, 11, 8, 45 is a tuesday at 8:45 AM
    target_datetime.date()
    target_datetime.tzname()
    """
  
    # put date in UTC timezone = London
    target_datetime.replace(tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc)
    target_datetime.tzname()

    # convert the future date to epoch time
    seconds_since_epoch = int(target_datetime.timestamp()) # google requires seconds as an int

    return seconds_since_epoch
In [21]:
# custom function to cross-join two arbitrary datasets


def df_crossjoin(df1, df2):
    """
    Function create the cartesian product of all rows between two dataframes
    
    # to use pandas merge function - create temporary keys in each dataframe, 
    # each row gets a matching key column
    # create the product of all rows from the left dataframe
    # with all rows on the right dataframe
    
    :param df1: first input dataframe (users or locations)
    :param df2: second input dataframe
    :return dataframe with cross-joined/product of inputs, with mulitindex
    """
    # disable `SettingWithCopyWarning` warning, we are intentionally working on a copy
    pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None  # default='warn'
    df1['_tmpkey'] = 1
    df2['_tmpkey'] = 1

    result_join = pd.merge(df1, df2, 
                           on='_tmpkey').drop('_tmpkey', axis=1)
    result_join.index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product((df1.index, df2.index))

    df1.drop('_tmpkey', axis=1, inplace=True)
    df2.drop('_tmpkey', axis=1, inplace=True)

    return result_join

# GOAL - create function that can be easily vectorized in Pandas using **`DataFrame.apply(lambda)`**
# to get distance matrix results


def get_single_google_distance(transit_mode, distance_units, origin_lat, origin_long, dest_lat, dest_long):
    """
    Function usees google distance matrix API to find distance & time between origin/destination pairs
    
    :param transit_mode: mode of travel; prefer rail (which is bus, rail, subway, etc.)
    :param distance_units: `metric`(returns km and meters) 
                           or `imperial` (returns miles/feet)
                           
    :param origin_lat: latitude of orgin
    :param origin_long: longitude of orgin
    
    :param dest_lat: latitude of destination
    :param dest_long: longitude of destination
    
    :return: list of distance matrix results to append as row: return status, 
             transit mode, distance units, and durations
    
    USEFUL NOTES:
    -- requires latitude/longitude for each point
    -- requires Google API key; ENV VAR: API_KEY_GOOGLE_DISTANCE
    -- docs:  https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/distance-matrix/intro
     
    Example - given:
    ...lat and long as strings
    origin =  '51.516892 -0.188303'
    destination = '51.572825 -0.23373000000000002'
    
    result returned: 
    {'distance': {'text': '12.1 km', 'value': 12079},   
      NOTE # returns two values, in `km` as string; and `value` in meters as int
    
    'duration': {'text': '50 mins', 'value': 3020},     
      NOTE # returns two values, in `minutes` as string; and `value` in seconds as int
    
    'status': 'OK'}                                     
      NOTE # return status of API request to google
    """
    
    # create API instance 
    gmaps = googlemaps.Client(key=API_KEY_GOOGLE_DISTANCE)
    
    # !important - origin & destination are
    # lat/long strings separated by a single space
    origin = str(origin_lat) + str(" ") + str(origin_long)
    destination = str(dest_lat) + str(" ") + str(dest_long)
    
    # call google api, returns one row as a dict
    g_results_dict = gmaps.distance_matrix(origin, destination, 
                                           units=distance_units, 
                                           mode=transit_mode
                                          )['rows'][0]['elements'][0]
    
    # decompose the dict into variables
    #  dict values have suffixes which  complicate dataframes and plotting 
    g_status = g_results_dict['status']
    # no suffix for time value, this is an int of seconds
    g_duration_sec = float(g_results_dict['duration']['value'])
    # returns in the form of:  x hours y min; must strip out suffix
    g_duration_min = g_results_dict['duration']['text']                
    # since minutes duration has hours/min text mixed in return
    # replace returned minutes with converted values of seconds
    g_duration_min = float(round(g_duration_sec/60,0))                     
    
    # handle different distance units & strip suffix as needed
    if distance_units == "metric":
        g_distance_km = (g_results_dict['distance']['text']).strip(" km")
        g_distance = float(g_distance_km)
        g_distance_2 = int(g_results_dict['distance']['value'])
            
    elif distance_units == "imperial":
        g_distance_miles = (g_results_dict['distance']['text']).strip(" miles")
        g_distance = float(g_distance_miles)
        g_distance_2 = int(g_results_dict['distance']['value'])
    
    results_dict = {'g_status': g_status,
                    'transit_mode': transit_mode, 
                    'distance_units': distance_units, 
                    'g_distance': g_distance, 
                    'g_distance_2': g_distance_2, 
                    'g_duration_min': g_duration_min, 
                    'g_duration_sec': g_duration_sec}
     
    results_list = [results_dict.get("g_status", "FAIL"),
                    results_dict.get("transit_mode", "NOT REQUESTED"),
                    results_dict.get("distance_units", "NOT REQUESTED"),
                    results_dict.get("g_distance", 0),
                    results_dict.get("g_distance_2", 0),
                    results_dict.get("g_duration_min", 0),
                    results_dict.get("g_duration_sec", 0)
                    ]

    return results_list

Recap what we've done in the background¶

  • data cleaning & EDA
  • taken our inputs of offices, projects, users/offices and users/projects
  • cleaned and corrected data
  • validated postcodes and geolocated with lat/long

  • cartesian joins
  • offices vs users of offices (~9,000 * 28 = 252K pairs)
  • projects vs users of projects (~33,000 * 361 = 11.9M pairs)

  • for all of these
  • captured google distance results
  • actual travel times/distances

# LIVE DEMO

# import folium libraries for mapping
import folium
from folium import plugins
from folium import FeatureGroup
from folium import LayerControl
from folium.plugins import HeatMap
from folium.plugins import MarkerCluster

# make geographic map - all users/offices
# assign map data to var; useful for switching datasets
map_data = london_all_users_offices

# setup map
# center of london lat long is:  51.5074° N, 0.1278° W
# we have people all over; leeds is further north:  53.8008° N, 1.5491° W
center_location=[51.5079, 0.0877]
map_all_users_offices = folium.Map(center_location,
                                   zoom_start = 6,
                                   zoom_control = True,
                                   control_scale = True,
                                   prefer_canvas = True,
                                   detect_retina = True,
                                   no_touch = True)

# change map style, comment out to use default
folium.TileLayer('Stamen Terrain').add_to(map_all_users_offices);  
# also try "openstreetmap", Stamen Terrain", “Mapbox Bright”, “Mapbox Control Room”,

# all of our origins and destinations are in a single DataFrame
# Ensure you're handing location points as floats
map_data['o_latitude'] = map_data['o_latitude'].astype(float)
map_data['o_longitude'] = map_data['o_longitude'].astype(float)
map_data['d_latitude'] = map_data['d_latitude'].astype(float)
map_data['d_longitude'] = map_data['d_longitude'].astype(float)

# create mappable data -- users
# map origins
origin_df = map_data[['o_latitude', 'o_longitude']]
origin_df = origin_df.dropna(axis=0, subset=['o_latitude','o_longitude'])

# List comprehension to make out list of lists; from dataframe
heat_data_origin = [[row['o_latitude'],row['o_longitude']] for index, row in map_data.iterrows()]

# create mappable data - offices
# group these and get unique, since there are so few
destination_df = map_data[['d_latitude', 'd_longitude', 'd_office']]

destination_df = destination_df.dropna(axis=0,
                                       subset=['d_latitude','d_longitude', 'd_office'])

# offices are duplicated many times per user; reduce this
destination_df = map_data[['d_latitude', 
                           'd_longitude', 'd_office']].drop_duplicates()    

# create heatmap layer of users
heat_data_destination = [[row['d_latitude'],
                          row['d_longitude'], 
                          row['d_office']] for index, row in destination_df.iterrows()]

# add markers
# center of London- London Bridge
folium.Marker(center_location,
              popup='London Bridge',
              icon=folium.Icon(color='darkred')
             ).add_to(map_all_users_offices);

# create markers for select offices
# put in a function to hide list of plot objects
def map_offices(destination_df):
   for i in range(0,len(destination_df)):
       print(i, destination_df.iloc[i]['d_office'])
       folium.Marker([destination_df.iloc[i]['d_latitude'], 
                      destination_df.iloc[i]['d_longitude']], 
                     popup=destination_df.iloc[i]['d_office'], 
                     icon=folium.Icon(color='darkblue', 
                                      icon='university', 
                                      prefix='fa')
                    ).add_to(map_all_users_offices)

map_offices(destination_df)

# plot heatmap; then display map
HeatMap(heat_data_origin).add_to(map_all_users_offices);
map_all_users_offices

# map_all_users_offices.save('index_map_all_users_offices.2018.12.06.html')
